ACUTE FEBRILE ILLNESS, HORSES - ICELAND: REQUEST FOR INFO
*********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
Date: Wed, 04 Mar 1998 11:27:05 -0100
From: Gumundur Petursson <gpet@rhi.hi.is>

During the last couple of weeks an acute febrile illness of horses has
spread rapidly in the Icelandic horses (ponies) in the greater Reykjavik
area. There are remarkably few clinical symptoms except for high fever (up
to 41Â°C), loss of appetite and lassitude. Leucopenia has also been
observed. The disease seems to run its course in 2-4 days. The incubation
period is apparently 2-10 days. There are practically no respiratory
symptoms. In some horses constipation followed by diarrhea is seen. The
veterinary authorities have stopped all export of Icelandic horses for the
time being.
Any suggestions as to the possible etiology of this epizootic and specific
tests to be carried out in order to obtain a quick diagnosis would be
welcome.
--
Gudmundur Petursson
Tilraunastod Haskola Islands i meinafraedi ad Keldum
(Institute for Experimental Pathology, University of Iceland)
